Evaluation¶

Alípio Jorge

A real example¶

  • Real situation
    • A hospital treats patients with Familial Amyloidotic Polyneuropathya
    • A disease with severe symptoms
    • Affects the nervous system
    • After diagnosis, it is not certain when the patient will have symptoms (onset)
    • A good prediction can lead to better treatment
    • this disease is commonly known as doença dos pezinhos
  • Remeber CRISP? This was the business problem

General approach¶

  • The machine learning problem
    • predict the time a patient takes to have symptoms of the disease (age of onset)
  • Approach skecthed:
    • Get the data
    • Define the features
    • Pre-process
    • Choose a learning algorithm
    • Determine hyper-parameters
    • Obtain a model
    • Check the model
    • Apply the model to real cases
    • Measure the operational performance

Modelling¶

  • Remember "what is machine learning?"
    • An algorithm that is able to improve its performance on a task
      • e.g. Predicting "age of onset"
    • Finding a function that approximates the unknown function that generates the data
      • Finding a model from the data
  • Evaluation is about measuring that performance
    • Can we trust the learned model?
    • Can we choose between competing models?
    • How can we available data to both learn and evaluate?
  • Besides: evaluation is often part of the learning process

Measuring performance in deployment¶

  • Our model predicts age of onset for new patients
    • What really counts:
      • lives we save
      • quality of life of the patients improved
      • reduction of cost that allows to treat more patients or spend money in other diseases
    • To measure the operational performance of our model
      • Predictive ability of the model
        • e.g., Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE)
      • Costs
        • cost matrix or cost function
  • While modelling we typically focus on the predictive ability
    • But we must always align model evaluation with deployment

Estimating operational performance¶

  • While we model we typically do not have access to the operational conditions
  • Our training data $X$ has a distribution $\mathcal{D}$
    • We assume in operation data has the same distribution
  • With this assumption we can estimate operational behavior from modeling behavior
  • We want to assess if our model generalizes well
    • It can give useful predictions over unseen data

When change happens¶

  • But the assumption does not always exactly hold
    • $\mathcal{D}$ may change with time (concept drift)
      • The model is less and less useful until becoming obsolete
      • We use a continuous learning approach
        • Data streams
        • Online learning
    • $\mathcal{D}$ may change abruptly (concept drift)
      • The model suddenly becomes obsolete
        • Change detection
    • New classes may appear
      • Novelty detection
    • And other real life nuisances

Training Error and Generalization Error¶

  • The aim of evaluation is to estimate Generalization Error from observed data $<X,Y>$

  • Error is a random variable

    • We want to estimate it as reliably (robustly) as possible

  • Training Error: average loss over the training sample ($x_i \in X_{train}$, $y_i \in Y_{train}$)

$$ \text{err}_{training}=\frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=1}^N L(y_i,\hat{f}(x_i)) $$
  • Test Error or generalization error: expected prediction error over an independent sample given a training set $T$
    • Notes:
      • We already have a model
      • The test set here is not fixed
$$ Err_{T} = \text{E}[L(y_i,\hat{f}(x_i))~|~T] $$
  • Expected Test Error: the training set is not fixed, so we can have different $\hat{f}(x)$
$$ Err = \text{E}[L(y_i,\hat{f}(x_i))] $$

Training Error¶

  • Training error is not a good estimate for the generalization error (in general)

    • Complex models can exploit data increasingly
    • Training error can go to zero due to overfitting
    • Generalization error is high

  • This applies to any predictive task:

    • Classification
    • Regression
    • Recommendation
    • etc.

Best general approach¶

  • Divide data in Train data, Validation data and Test data
    • Train: fit models (e.g. find parameters)
    • Validation: used for model selection
      • including hyper parameter tuning
    • Test: assessment of the final model
      • Test data should not be seen before final validation

Bias-Variance Decomposition¶

  • We assume that $Y = f(X) + \epsilon$

    • $f$ is the true function
    • $\epsilon$ is the irreducible error

  • If we consider the squared-error loss

$$ \text{Err}(x_0) = \text{E}[(Y-\hat{f}(x_0))^2 |X=x_0] $$
  • From which we can get to
$$ \text{Err}(x_0) = \text{Irreducibe Error}+\text{Bias}^2+\text{Variance} $$
  • More complex models tend to have lower bias error and higher variance error

Optimism of the training error rate¶

  • The training error is optimistic
$$ \text{err}_{training} < \text{Err}_T $$

  • Why (intuitivelly)?

    • Learning minimizes error for the sample
    • The more expressive (complex) the model, the more error is minimized

  • With $N$ training cases, it can be shown for squared error, 0-1 and other loss functions that optimism is at least

$$ \frac{2}{N}\sum_{i=1}^{N}\text{Cov}(\hat{y}_i,y_i) $$
  • Overfitting increases the difference between true $y$ and predicted
    • Increasing $\text{Cov}(\hat{y}_i,y_i)$

Cross-Validation¶

  • K-Fold Cross Validation

    • Split the sample in $k$ segments of equal size (folds)
    • Use all folds but one to train a model
    • Use the remaining fold for error assessment (validation)
    • Average error over folds

  • Cross Validation estimates the Expected Test Error

    • Independent of sample
    • Each fold has a different training set

  • Leave-one-out

    • If the sample is very small we can make $K=N$
    • We train with all examples but one in each iteration
    • Leave-one-put still estimates Expected Test Error

Choosing the K in KFCV¶

  • $K=N$
    • Provides an approximately unbiased estimator of $\text{Err}$
    • High variance
    • Computationally expensive
  • $K=5$
    • Lower variance
    • Bias can be a problem
      • Training sets are smaller
      • Easier to overfit
      • Error can be overestimated
      • Not a problem with enough data
  • 5 or 10 fold-CV are recommended in general

Pitfalls when using CV¶

  • Imagine:

    • We have a genomics data-set
    • 50 examples and 5000 predictors
    • 2 equal-size classes with random labels

  • (Wrong) Procedure:

    • Identify a subset of the predictors with high correlation with the target
    • Use CV to tune hyper-parameters and estimate the error

  • What can go wrong?

    • Expected error is 50% but it can get as low as 3%

  • What was the problem?

    • We used test data for selecting predictors (data leakage)
    • Error grossly underestimated

Pitfalls when using CV¶

  • Correct procedure
    • Divide the dataset into $K$ folds
    • For each fold $k$:
      • Find good predictors
      • Build the classifier from all folds but one
      • Predict class labels in fold $k$

Pitfalls when using CV¶

  • Other situations:

    • Build features with the whole dataset
    • Discretize with the whole dataset
    • Impute values with the whole dataset
    • etc.

  • In general:

    • CV must be applied to the whole process

  • General rule:

    • Think of the operational conditions
    • Training cannot benefit from test data

Pitfalls when using CV¶

  • Class Imbalance
    • Fraud detection
      • One class has 97% of the cases
  • Normal cross validation
    • Some folds may have very little or no cases of the small class
    • Error is over-estimated
  • Stratified cross validation
    • Each fold has approximately the same proportion as the whole data set

Bootstrap Method¶

  • Bootstrap is a general statistical tool

    • It can be used to estimate $\text{Err}$

  • The procedure for a dataset $D$:

    • Obtain $B$ bootstrap samples of $D$ with replacement (same $N$)
    • For each sample $S$:
      • Obtain a model with $S$
      • Assess the model on the cases that were not selected for $S$

  • How many cases we have for testing?

    • Approximately 36.8% of $N$

Bootstrap Method¶

  • The downside of bootstrap

    • $N \times 0.638$ can be small and have high bias
    • Testing samples may overlap (not independent)
      • Therefore more samples are needed
      • Higher computational costs

  • Can bootstrap be preferable to Cross-Validation?

    • Not really
    • Bootstrap can iterate almost indefinitely reducing variance
    • But we can also use Repeated k-fold cross validation

Summary so far¶

  • The aim is to estimate Generalization Error
  • Error can be estimated empirically
  • Estimating error with the training set is optimistic
    • Especially for complex/expressive models
  • Train, Validation, Test separation
  • Cross validation provides a balanced estimate of the Expected Test Error
  • Bootstrap is an alternative no CV, but hardly preferred

Question¶

  • How to distinguish two solutions with very similar error values?

Measuring statistical significance¶

  • We compare two algorithms A and B using CV
    • A has 0.8832 accuracy
    • B has 0.8845 accuracy
  • Is this difference important?
    • Statistical significance
      • the difference occurs most of the time
      • how likely is it to observe this difference or larger?
    • Usefulness
      • st. significant does not imply useful
      • does it save more lifes with fewer secondary effects?

Measuring statistical significance¶

  • Use Hypothesis testing
  • 10 fold CV example with t-test
    • obtain two samples of the accuracies: $Acc_A$ and $Acc_B$
    • calculate the means $mean_A$ and $mean_B$
    • we assume that the accuracy values follow a t-distribution with $k-1$ degrees of freedom
    • we can use a paired t-test
    • $H_0$ or Null hypothesis is that the difference of means is zero
    • the paired t-test checks if we can reject $H_0$
    • the test assumes independence of the samples (not true)

More on statistical significance tests¶

  • t-test with cross validation should be avoided
    • the independence of the values does not exist
    • it gives some information though
  • if we have enough data to promote independence
    • t-test is acceptable
  • To compare two algorithms on multiple datasets (e.g. 30)
    • cross-validate on each dataset
    • choose a level of significance (typically 1% to 5%)
    • if assumptions hold use a parametric test (t-test)
    • if not, use non-parametric wilcoxon signed rank test
  • To compare many algorithms on multiple datasets
    • use Friedman test and post-hoc Nemenyi with critical distances
  • Be careful with multiple comparisons
    • sometimes we have to adjust the p-values
